{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654522"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18621"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18621"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76475"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11353"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18621"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61972"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10268"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26347"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26354"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76475"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring intense exercise, skeletal muscle cells must rapidly generate ATP when oxygen delivery cannot meet demand. This requires a shift to anaerobic metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes anaerobic glycolysis in skeletal muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Yields more ATP than aerobic metabolism","Occurs primarily in mitochondria","Generates carbon dioxide as end product","Produces 2 ATP molecules per glucose molecule","Requires oxygen as final electron acceptor"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAnaerobic glycolysis \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduces 2 ATP molecules per glucose molecule\u003C/strong\u003E through substrate-level phosphorylation in the cytoplasm. This process generates lactate as the end product and does not require oxygen, making it crucial during intense exercise when oxygen demand exceeds supply.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequires oxygen as final electron acceptor\u003C/strong\u003E - Anaerobic glycolysis by definition occurs without oxygen; instead it uses pyruvate as the electron acceptor to form lactate\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerates carbon dioxide as end product\u003C/strong\u003E - Carbon dioxide is produced during aerobic metabolism in the citric acid cycle, not during anaerobic glycolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccurs primarily in mitochondria\u003C/strong\u003E - Anaerobic glycolysis takes place entirely in the cytoplasm, while aerobic metabolism occurs in mitochondria\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYields more ATP than aerobic metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E - Anaerobic glycolysis produces much less ATP (2 molecules) compared to complete aerobic glucose oxidation (up to 36 ATP molecules)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile anaerobic glycolysis is less efficient in terms of ATP yield per glucose molecule, it can produce ATP at a faster rate than aerobic metabolism, making it essential for brief periods of intense muscle activity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anaerobic glycolysis produces 2 ATP molecules per glucose molecule without requiring oxygen.","Lactate is the end product of anaerobic glycolysis in skeletal muscle during intense exercise.","The rate of ATP production through anaerobic glycolysis is faster than aerobic metabolism."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61972"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18621"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61972"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T14:33:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T14:34:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11353"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76475"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt"